Only in 1879 was it possible to obtain a carcass of a bird, and in 1901 a nest was discovered. Many aspects of the life of the black american swift remain unknown, in particular, there is not enough information on molting and migration of birds. to vulnerable species, the bird is protected in the United States at the national level. The International Union of Ornithologists classifies the black American swift as an American swift (Cypseloides) and distinguishes three subspecies. The swift is 15–18 cm long and weighs 35–45 g [2] (35 g is Cypseloides niger costaricensis, 45 g - mass of Cypseloides niger borealis [3]).